<h5>
    Procedure and Questions
</h5>

<p>
    <strong>Note:</strong>
    All of the switches in the circuit diagrams for this lab
    are being drawn as open switch. This is because it is much easier to see them.
    Obviously, the point is to open and close the switch after you
    build it to see how it works.
</p>

<ol>
    <li>
        Start with a circuit containing
        just a light bulb and a battery:
        <br>
        <div id = 'simpleCircuit'></div>
        <br>
        Then, add a switch <emph>in series</emph>
        with the light bulb, like this:
        <br>
        <div id = 'switchInSeries'></div>
        Move the switch up and down. (by clicking on it)
        Does it work?
    </li>
    <li>
        What happens to the moving electrons in the circuit
        when the switch is open?
        Do they move partially or stop moving entirely?
    </li>
    <li>
        Now try rewiring
        your circuit so that the switch is connected
        to the light bulb <emph>in parallel</emph>:
        <br>
        <div id = 'switchInParallel'></div>
        Try flipping the switch on and off.
        It should still work, because when you switch it the light bulb
        changes between bright and dim.....but you will notice something a little strange.
        What?
    </li>
    <li>
        I like to call this a "reverse switch." Why does that name fit?
    </li>
    <li>
        When the switch is on, what happens to the battery. Why?
        You can look back at the previous lab on <a href = '/labs/shortCircuits'>short circuits</a>
        for guidance.
    </li>
    <li>
        Using information from the previous lab on <a href = '/labs/shortCircuits'>short circuits</a>,
        answer these questions:
        Why is the light bulb off when the switch is on?
        Why is the light bulb on when the battery is off?
    </li>
    <li>
        If you want a switch to properly control a light bulb,
        do yo want to connect it in series or parallel with the light bulb?
        Give two reasons why:
        one reason that deals with safety and another with making your circuit easy to understand.
    </li>
</ol>


<script>
    let simpleCircuit = new CircuitDiagram();
    simpleCircuit.addCellSimple('up',3);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('up',1);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('right',4);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('down',2);
    simpleCircuit.addLightBulb('down',1);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('down',2);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('left',4);
    simpleCircuit.addWire('up',1);

    let switchInSeries = new CircuitDiagram();
    switchInSeries.addCellSimple('up',3);
    switchInSeries.addWire('up',1);
    switchInSeries.addWire('right',1.5);
    switchInSeries.addOpenSwitch('right',1);
    switchInSeries.addWire('right',1.5);
    switchInSeries.addWire('down',2);
    switchInSeries.addLightBulb('down',1);
    switchInSeries.addWire('down',2);
    switchInSeries.addWire('left',4);
    switchInSeries.addWire('up',1);

    let switchInParallel = new CircuitDiagram();
    switchInParallel.addCellSimple('up',3);
    switchInParallel.addWire('up',1);
    switchInParallel.addWire('right',4);
    switchInParallel.addWire('down',2);
    switchInParallel.addLightBulb('down',1);
    switchInParallel.addWire('down',2);
    switchInParallel.translateCursor('up',5);
    switchInParallel.addWire('right',3);
    switchInParallel.addWire('down',2);
    switchInParallel.addOpenSwitch('down',1);
    switchInParallel.addWire('down',2);
    switchInParallel.addWire('left',3);
    switchInParallel.addWire('left',4);
    switchInParallel.addWire('up',1);

    $("#simpleCircuit").append(simpleCircuit.drawCanvas(200));
    $("#switchInSeries").append(switchInSeries.drawCanvas(400));
    $("#switchInParallel").append(switchInParallel.drawCanvas(400));
</script>